#People per household

K-Means

Methodology

First we are going to look at some K-Means clustering on the census variables that we have created.

The first thing we need to do is to estimate how many clusters we need to build. To do this we run the k-means algorithm across an array of different values of k and make an estimate based on the Within Cluster Sum of Squares WSS.


We try to choose k where there is an elbow in the plot or where adding another cluster does not improve WSS much

#cluster using kmeans - Scaled Data
wss <- (nrow(data_ED_scale)-1)*sum(apply(data_ED_scale,2,var))
for (i in 2:100) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(data_ED_scale,
                                      centers=i,iter.max=30)$withinss)
plot(1:100, wss, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters",
     ylab="Within groups sum of squares")

It looks as though 6 clusters might be appropriate and so we re-run the k-means algorithm with 6 clusters selected.

k=6

KM_Cluster_scale = kmeans(data_ED_scale,centers=k,iter.max=30)

Partioning Around Medoids PAM

Methodology

After looking at K-Means, we look at an alternative methodology, K-medoids or PAM. Again the first thing to do is to select the ideal number of clusters.

In this instance we will use the Average Silhouette to choose the optimal number of clusters, with the largest silhouette indicating the best.

# Determine number of clusters 
asw <- numeric(20)

## Note that "k=1" won't work! 
for (k in 2:20) 
  asw[k] <- pam(data_ED, k) $ silinfo $ avg.width 
k.best <- which.max(asw) 
cat("silhouette-optimal number of clusters:", k.best, "\n") 
## silhouette-optimal number of clusters: 2
plot(1:20, asw, type= "h", main = "pam() clustering assessment", 
     xlab= "k  (# clusters)", ylab = "average silhouette width") 
axis(1, k.best, paste("best",k.best,sep="\n"), col = "red", col.axis = "red")

The graph indicates that 2 clusters are most appropriate so again we run the algorithm with this input

pam = pam(data_ED_scale, k.best)
